content.text:
CSS doesn't support that syntax — `@keyframes` only accepts a single name per rule.

However, there's a cleaner solution: set `text-decoration-color: currentColor` on links, then have links use the existing `header` keyframe. Since `currentColor` always mirrors the `color` property, the wavy underline will animate in sync automatically — no new keyframe needed at all.

Updated plan:

**`css/style.css` — `a, a:visited` block only:**
```css
a, a:visited {
    color: hsl(272, 20%, 58%);
    text-underline-position: under;
    text-decoration: wavy underline currentColor;
    -webkit-animation: header 5s ease forwards infinite;
    animation: header 5s ease forwards infinite;
}
```

That's the only change needed. No new keyframes, no duplication.

