Yes — a real one. Modern screen readers (VoiceOver, NVDA, JAWS) now read CSS `content` values including emoji, so every list item would be announced with "fishcake with swirl" before it. That's decorative noise repeated on every bullet.

**The fix** is the CSS alt-text slash syntax, which sets an empty accessible label:

```css
ul li:before {
    content: '🍥' / '';   /* visually shows emoji, screen readers skip it */
    margin-left: -1.6em;
    padding-right: 0.5em;
}
```

The `/ ''` part tells the accessibility tree to treat it as presentational. This is supported in Chrome 99+, Firefox 107+, and Safari 15.4+.

